\(\therefore \overrightarrow{\mathrm{P}} \perp \overrightarrow{\mathrm{F}} \text { i.e. } 90^{\circ}\)

quest_title: When HCl  gas is passed through a saturated solution of NaCl the solubility of NaCl
explanation_txt:
The dissociation of \(NaCl\) is:

\(NaCl \rightleftharpoons Na^++Cl^-\)

When \(HCl\) dissociates it increases concentration of \(Cl^-\) ions and pushes the reaction backwards. So, less \(NaCl\) dissolves. [\(NaCl\) is said to dissolve if it dissociates into \(Na^+\) and \(Cl^-\)]. Hence, solubility decreases.

quest_title: When electron jump from \({3}^{rd}\) energy level to second energy level then wavelength of radiation is \(\lambda\)\({}_{o}\). The wavelength of radiation when electron jump from fourth energy level to second energy level is
explanation_txt:
When electron jump from \(3^{\text {rd }}\) energy level to \(2^{\text {nd }}\) energy level
\(\cfrac{\mathrm{hc}}{\lambda_{\mathrm{a}}}=\mathrm{E}_{3}-\mathrm{E}_{2}\)
or, \(\cfrac{\mathrm{hc}}{\lambda_{\mathrm{a}}}=\cfrac{-13.6}{9}+\cfrac{13.6}{4}\)
Or, \(\lambda_{\mathrm{a}}=\cfrac{\mathrm{hc} \times 36}{13.6 \times 5} \cdots \cdots \cdots(1)\)
When electron jump from \(4^{\text {th }}\) energy level to second energy level then
\(\cfrac{\mathrm{hc}}{\lambda}=\mathrm{E}_{4}-\mathrm{E}_{2}\)
or, \(\cfrac{\mathrm{hc}}{\lambda}=\cfrac{-13.6}{16}+\cfrac{13.6}{4}\)
or, \(\lambda=\cfrac{\mathrm{hc} \times 16}{13.6 \times 3} \cdots \cdots \cdots(2)\)
Dividing ( 2) by ( 1)
\(\cfrac{\lambda}{\lambda_{a}}=\cfrac{16}{3} \times \cfrac{5}{36}\)
or, \(\lambda=\cfrac{20 \lambda_{\mathrm{a}}}{27}\)
